What is a daemon?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl601\sa540\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs36 \cf4 \cb3 In computing, a daemon (pronounced DEE-muhn) is a program that runs continuously as a background process and wakes up to handle periodic service requests, which often come from remote processes. The daemon program is alerted to the request by the operating system (OS), and it either responds to the request itself or forwards the request to another program or process as appropriate.\cb1 \
\cb3 Common daemon processes include print spoolers, email handlers and other programs that manage administrative tasks. Many Unix or Linux utility programs run as daemons. For example, on Linux, the Network Time Protocol ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.techtarget.com/searchnetworking/definition/Network-Time-Protocol"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 NTP}}) daemon is used to measure time differences between the clock on the computer it runs on and those of all other computers on the network. A time daemon runs on each of the host computers, with one being designated as primary and all others as secondary. Secondary daemons reset the network time on their host computer by first sending a request to the primary time daemon to find out the correct network time.\cb1 \
\cb3 A daemon plays the role of a server in a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.techtarget.com/searchnetworking/definition/client-server"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 client-server}}\'a0model.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl560\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 What role do daemons play in web services?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl601\sa540\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs36 \cf4 \cb3 One of the most obvious examples of a daemon is the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.techtarget.com/whatis/definition/HTTP-Hypertext-Transfer-Protocol"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 Hypertext Transfer Protocol}}\'a0daemon (HTTPd), which runs on every web server, continually waiting in dormant mode until requests come in from web clients and their users. Earlier versions of HTTP daemons would spawn a new process to handle each request. The new process, a replica of the daemon, would fetch the requested content and return it to the requesting client. Then, the new process would die.\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \cb3 By spawning a new process, the original process could go back to dormant mode to wait for other requests. This approach was used to prevent the original process from getting too busy to service new requests, as a daemon that handles all requests by itself would make a system more vulnerable to hackers.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.techtarget.com/searchsecurity/definition/denial-of-service"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 Denial-of-service attacks}}\'a0are often based on the strategy of keeping a daemon too busy to handle incoming requests.\cb1 \
\cb3 More modern HTTP daemons, such as Apache, handle requests using threads instead of spawning new processes. Threads, which came into common use well after the first generation of HTTP daemons were implemented and deployed, enable different parts of the same process to run in parallel. The main part of a daemon can wait for new requests, while other threads handle older requests. Threads require less overhead than spawning a new process, which takes time to accomplish, and the new process needs memory to run.\cb1 \
\cb3 A third approach is exemplified by the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nginx.com/resources/glossary/nginx/"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 Nginx HTTP}}\'a0daemon, which is based on an event-driven architecture operating in a single thread. Requests are handed off to worker processes, which constantly run in the background -- that is, they aren't spawned just to handle a request only to die off immediately afterward. The administrator determines how many worker processes to create.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl560\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 What kind of operating systems do daemons require?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl601\sa540\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs36 \cf4 \cb3 Since daemons require special services from the OS, they behave slightly differently from one operating system to another. The first daemons were run on the Unix OS and were designed around the features of Unix.\cb1 \
\cb3 Daemons are started on the Unix command line or in a startup file; these files contain script that is executed when the system is booted or on some other event, such as user login or when a new\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.techtarget.com/searchdatacenter/definition/shell-script"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 shell script}}\'a0is spawned. They then run in the background and wait for a signal from the OS to wake up and go into action.\cb1 \
\cb3 Daemons can only run on\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.techtarget.com/whatis/definition/multitasking"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 multitasking}}\'a0OSes. They were implemented in Microsoft Windows, starting with the NT version, and are often referred to as\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/framework/windows-services/introduction-to-windows-service-applications"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 Windows services}}\'a0instead of daemons.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl560\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 What are examples of daemons?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl601\sa540\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs36 \cf4 \cb3 Daemons respond to alerts from the OS upon some external event, such as the arrival of a message on the network. For messages coming from the network, the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.techtarget.com/searchnetworking/definition/TCP-IP"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 TCP/IP}}\'a0module on the host computer looks up the port number of the message and sends an alert to the daemon assigned to that port number. For example, port number 80 is assigned to HTTP, so when a message with that port number is received, the TCP/IP stack built into the OS sends a signal to the HTTPd.\cb1 \
\cb3 Any system based on Unix or on a variant of Unix runs several daemons, the names of which typically end with the letter\'a0
\f2\i d
\f1\i0 . The following are some examples of daemons:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sl601\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
init.\'a0
\f1\b0 This is the first daemon to start up when Unix boots, and it spawns all other processes.\cb1 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
inetd.\'a0
\f1\b0 This super-daemon listens for internet requests on a designated port number and spawns the appropriate server program to handle them. Services handled by inetd include rlogin, telnet, ftp, talk and finger.\cb1 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
crond.\'a0
\f1\b0 This daemon executes scheduled commands.\cb1 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
dhcpd.\'a0
\f1\b0 This daemon provides\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.techtarget.com/searchnetworking/definition/DHCP"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol}}\'a0services.\cb1 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
fingerd.\'a0
\f1\b0 This daemon is often started by inetd to respond to the finger command.\cb1 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
ftpd.\'a0
\f1\b0 This daemon is often started by inetd to handle\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.techtarget.com/searchnetworking/definition/File-Transfer-Protocol-FTP"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \ul \ulc5 File Transfer Protocol}}\'a0requests.\cb1 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
httpd.
\f1\b0 \'a0This daemon acts as a web server.\
