\f3\fs32 \cf6 \cb3 \'a0The key differentiator between containers and virtual machines is that virtual machines virtualize an entire machine down to the hardware layers and containers only virtualize software layers above the operating system level.
\f1\fs36 \cf4 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f4\b \cf7 \cb3 \'a0Introduction
\f5\b0 \
Docker image is a stack of read-only layers wherein each layer a Docker command is recorded. When we start a Docker container from Docker images, the Docker engine takes the read-only stack of layers and adds a read-write stack on top of it. The changes which we make within a running container will be stored on this read-write layer. This file system of Docker is known as the Union File System. Docker also ensures that the changes on read-write will not affect the original files in the read-only layer.\'a0
\f1 \cf4 \cb1 \

\f4\b\fs32 \cf7 \cb3 The Requirement of Docker Volumes
\f5\b0 \cb1 \

\fs36 \cb3 Since the files created or modified inside a container will be stored on a writable container layer, the data doesn\'92t persist when the container no longer exists. Also, it isn\'92t easy to get the data out of a container if another process needs it. The Union File system is provided by a storage driver using Linux kernels. When we use the writable container layer, we have an extra abstraction with a storage driver, which reduces the performance.\cb1 \

\f4\b \cb3 Different Types of Storage Options
\f5\b0 \cb1 \
\cb3 Docker has multiple options for containers to store files in the host machine.\cb1 \
