\f4\b \cf7 \cb3 Volumes
\f5\b0 \cb1 \
\cb3 Volumes are also stored as part of the host file system, which is managed by Docker. On Linux, volumes are stored in\'a0
\f6\i \'93
\f5\i0 /var/lib/docker/volume
\f6\i \'94.\'a0
\f5\i0 Non-Docker processes should not be allowed to modify this part of the file system. One of the best ways to persist data in Docker is Volumes
\f7 \cf8 \cb9 \

\f4\b \cf7 \cb3 Bind Mounts
\f5\b0 \cb1 \
\cb3 \'93Bind mounts\'94 can be stored anywhere on the host system, which may even contain important system files or directories. In this case, Non-Docker processes on the Docker host or a Docker container can modify them at any time. If you bind-mount into a non-empty directory on the container, the directory\'92s existing contents are obscured by the bind mount.\cb1 \

\f4\b \cb3 \'a0Difference between Bind Mount and Volume Mount
\f5\b0 \cb1 \
\cb3 Bind mounts are basically just binding a certain directory or file from the host inside the container. The file or directory is referenced by its absolute path on the host machine.\cb1 \
\cb3 When you use a volume, a new directory is created within Docker\'92s storage directory on the host machine, and Docker manages that directory\'92s contents.\cb1 \
\cb3 If you use binds and want to transfer your containers/applications to another host, you have to rebuild your directory-structure, whereas volumes are more uniform on every host.\cb1 \

\f4\b \cb3 tmpfs mounts
\f5\b0 \cb1 \
\cb3 tmpfs mounts are temporary. They are stored in the host system\'92s memory only and are never written to the host system\'92s file system. If your container generates non-persistent state data, consider using a tmpfs mount to avoid storing the data anywhere permanently and increase the container\'92s performance by avoiding writing into the container\'92s writable layer. This option can be used for keeping sensitive data during execution.\cf3 \cb1 \
