\fs36 \cf8 \cb3 Volumes are the preferred mechanism for persisting data generated by and used by Docker containers. While\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://docs.docker.com/storage/bind-mounts/"}}{\fldrslt \cf13 bind mounts}}\'a0are dependent on the directory structure and OS of the host machine, volumes are completely managed by Docker. Volumes have several advantages over bind mounts:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sl320\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0\cf8 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Volumes are easier to back up or migrate than bind mounts.\cb1 \
\ls6\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
You can manage volumes using Docker CLI commands or the Docker API.\cb1 \
\ls6\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Volumes work on both Linux and Windows containers.\cb1 \
\ls6\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Volumes can be more safely shared among multiple containers.\cb1 \
\ls6\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Volume drivers let you store volumes on remote hosts or cloud providers, to encrypt the contents of volumes, or to add other functionality.\cb1 \
\ls6\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
New volumes can have their content pre-populated by a container.\cb1 \
\ls6\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
