\fs48 \cf8 \cb3 The underlying technology\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl480\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf8 \cb3 Docker is written in the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://golang.org/"}}{\fldrslt \cf13 \cb3 Go programming language}}\'a0and takes advantage of several features of the Linux kernel to deliver its functionality. Docker uses a technology called\'a0
\f7\fs25\fsmilli12600 \cf13 \cb14 namespaces
\f8\fs28 \cf8 \cb3 \'a0to provide the isolated workspace called the\'a0
\f9\i \cf8 \cb3 container
\f8\i0 \cf8 \cb3 . When you run a container, Docker creates a set of\'a0
\f9\i \cf8 \cb3 namespaces
\f8\i0 \cf8 \cb3 \'a0for that container.\
These namespaces provide a layer of isolation. Each aspect of a container runs in a separate namespace and its access is limited to that namespace.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl740\partightenfactor0

\f12\i\b\fs60 \cf20 \cb3 \'93Namespaces are a feature of the Linux kernel that partitions kernel resources such that one set of processes sees one set of resources while another set of processes sees a different set of resources.\'94\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl960\sa384\partightenfactor0

\f11\i0\fs76\fsmilli38400 \cf21 What Are Namespaces?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf22 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl540\sa450\partightenfactor0

\f3\b0\fs30 \cf20 \cb3 Namespaces have been part of the Linux kernel since about\'a02002, and over time more tooling and namespace types have been added. Real container support was added to the Linux kernel only in\'a02013, however. This is what made namespaces really useful and brought them to the masses.\
But what are namespaces exactly? Here\'92s a wordy definition from\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linux_namespaces"}}{\fldrslt 
\f13\b \cf22 Wikipedia}}:\
\pard\pardeftab720\li400\sl540\sa300\partightenfactor0

\f12\i\b\fs60 \cf20 \'93Namespaces are a feature of the Linux kernel that partitions kernel resources such that one set of processes sees one set of resources while another set of processes sees a different set of resources.\'94\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl540\sa450\partightenfactor0

\f3\i0\b0\fs30 \cf20 In other words, the key feature of namespaces is that they isolate processes from each other. On a server where you are running many different services, isolating each service and its associated processes from other services means that there is a smaller blast radius for changes, as well as a smaller footprint for security\uc0\u8209 related concerns. Mostly though, isolating services meets the architectural style of microservices as described by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://martinfowler.com/articles/microservices.html"}}{\fldrslt 
\f13\b \cf22 Martin Fowler}}.\
Using containers during the development process gives the developer an isolated environment that looks and feels like a complete VM. It\'92s not a VM, though\'a0\'96 it\'92s a process running on a server somewhere. If the developer starts two containers, there are two processes running on a single server somewhere\'a0\'96 but they are isolated from each other.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl660\sa264\partightenfactor0

\f11\b\fs52\fsmilli26400 \cf21 Types of Namespaces\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl540\sa450\partightenfactor0

\f3\b0\fs30 \cf20 Within the Linux kernel, there are different types of namespaces. Each namespace has its own unique properties:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sl440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0
\fs36 \cf20 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 		\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/user_namespaces.7.html"}}{\fldrslt 
\f13\b\fs30 \cf22 user namespace}}\'a0has its own set of user IDs and group IDs for assignment to processes. In particular, this means that a process can have\'a0
\f14 \cf21 root
\f3 \cf20 \'a0privilege within its user namespace without having it in other user namespaces.\cb1 \
\ls10\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 		\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/pid_namespaces.7.html"}}{\fldrslt 
\f13\b\fs30 \cf22 process ID (PID) namespace}}\'a0assigns a set of PIDs to processes that are independent from the set of PIDs in other namespaces. The first process created in a new namespace has PID\'a01 and child processes are assigned subsequent PIDs. If a child process is created with its own PID namespace, it has PID\'a01 in that namespace as well as its PID in the parent process\'92 namespace. See\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nginx.com/blog/what-are-namespaces-cgroups-how-do-they-work/#pid-namespaces"}}{\fldrslt 
\f13\b\fs30 \cf22 below}}\'a0for an example.\cb1 \
\ls10\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 		\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/network_namespaces.7.html"}}{\fldrslt 
\f13\b\fs30 \cf22 network namespace}}\'a0has an independent network stack: its own private routing table, set of IP addresses, socket listing, connection tracking table, firewall, and other network\uc0\u8209 related resources.\cb1 \
\ls10\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 		\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/mount_namespaces.7.html"}}{\fldrslt 
\f13\b\fs30 \cf22 mount namespace}}\'a0has an independent list of mount points seen by the processes in the namespace. This means that you can mount and unmount filesystems in a mount namespace without affecting the host filesystem.\cb1 \
\ls10\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 		\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
An\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/ipc_namespaces.7.html"}}{\fldrslt 
\f13\b\fs30 \cf22 interprocess communication (IPC) namespace}}\'a0has its own IPC resources, for example\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/mq_overview.7.html"}}{\fldrslt 
\f13\b\fs30 \cf22 POSIX message queues}}.\cb1 \
\ls10\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 		\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/uts_namespaces.7.html"}}{\fldrslt 
\f13\b\fs30 \cf22 UNIX Time\uc0\u8209 Sharing (UTS) namespace}}\'a0allows a single system to appear to have different host and domain names to different processes.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl660\sa264\partightenfactor0

