\f8\fs60 \cf8 Use bridge networks\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl480\sa320\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf8 \cb3 \
In terms of networking, a bridge network is a Link Layer device which forwards traffic between network segments. A bridge can be a hardware device or a software device running within a host machine\'92s kernel.\
In terms of Docker, a bridge network uses a software bridge which allows containers connected to the same bridge network to communicate, while providing isolation from containers which are not connected to that bridge network. The Docker bridge driver automatically installs rules in the host machine so that containers on different bridge networks cannot communicate directly with each other.\
Bridge networks apply to containers running on the\'a0
\f11\b \cf8 \cb3 same
\f8\b0 \cf8 \cb3 \'a0Docker daemon host. For communication among containers running on different Docker daemon hosts, you can either manage routing at the OS level, or you can use an\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://docs.docker.com/network/overlay/"}}{\fldrslt \cf13 \cb3 overlay network}}.\
When you start Docker, a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://docs.docker.com/network/bridge/#use-the-default-bridge-network"}}{\fldrslt \cf13 \cb3 default bridge network}}\'a0(also called\'a0
\f7\fs25\fsmilli12600 \cf13 \cb14 bridge
\f8\fs28 \cf8 \cb3 ) is created automatically, and newly-started containers connect to it unless otherwise specified. You can also create user-defined custom bridge networks.\'a0
\f11\b \cf8 \cb3 User-defined bridge networks are superior to the default\'a0
\f15\fs25\fsmilli12600 \cf13 \cb14 bridge
\f11\fs28 \cf8 \cb3 \'a0network.
\f8\b0 \cf8 \cb3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl560\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs48 \cf8 \cb3 Differences between user-defined bridges and the default bridge\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sl480\sa320\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0
\f11\b\fs24 \cf8 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
User-defined bridges provide automatic DNS resolution between containers
\f8\b0 .\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb3 Containers on the default bridge network can only access each other by IP addresses, unless you use the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://docs.docker.com/network/links/"}}{\fldrslt 
\f7\fs25\fsmilli12600 \cf13 \cb14 --link
\f8\fs24 \cb3 \'a0option}}, which is considered legacy. On a user-defined bridge network, containers can resolve each other by name or alias.\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb3 Imagine an application with a web front-end and a database back-end. If you call your containers\'a0
\f7\fs25\fsmilli12600 \cf13 \cb14 web
\f8\fs24 \cf8 \cb3 \'a0and\'a0
\f7\fs25\fsmilli12600 \cf13 \cb14 db
\f8\fs24 \cf8 \cb3 , the web container can connect to the db container at\'a0
\f7\fs25\fsmilli12600 \cf13 \cb14 db
\f8\fs24 \cf8 \cb3 , no matter which Docker host the application stack is running on.\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb3 If you run the same application stack on the default bridge network, you need to manually create links between the containers (using the legacy\'a0
\f7\fs25\fsmilli12600 \cf13 \cb14 --link
\f8\fs24 \cf8 \cb3 \'a0flag). These links need to be created in both directions, so you can see this gets complex with more than two containers which need to communicate. Alternatively, you can manipulate the\'a0
\f7\fs25\fsmilli12600 \cf13 \cb14 /etc/hosts
\f8\fs24 \cf8 \cb3 \'a0files within the containers, but this creates problems that are difficult to debug.\cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\fs28 \
\ls12\ilvl0
\f11\b\fs24 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
User-defined bridges provide better isolation
\f8\b0 .\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb3 All containers without a\'a0
\f7\fs25\fsmilli12600 \cf13 \cb14 --network
\f8\fs24 \cf8 \cb3 \'a0specified, are attached to the default bridge network. This can be a risk, as unrelated stacks/services/containers are then able to communicate.\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb3 Using a user-defined network provides a scoped network in which only containers attached to that network are able to communicate.\cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\fs28 \
\ls12\ilvl0
\f11\b\fs24 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Containers can be attached and detached from user-defined networks on the fly
\f8\b0 .\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb3 During a container\'92s lifetime, you can connect or disconnect it from user-defined networks on the fly. To remove a container from the default bridge network, you need to stop the container and recreate it with different network options.\cb1 \uc0\u8232 
